  <static seed="77" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicMath/FractionsCalculation/AddThreeFractions30.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{ {{\frac{1}{6}}} + {{\frac{1}{5}}} + {{\frac{1}{10}}} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{7}{15}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add fractions with different denominators, we need to find the common denominator first. One way is to list the multiples of the largest denominator, until all <m>3</m> denominators divide into the multiple.</p>
<p>The largest denominator is <m>10</m>. We list its first few multiples:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ 10, 20, 30 }</m></p>
<p>Note that all denominators, <m>6, 5 \text{ and } 10</m> each divide into <m>30</m>.</p>
<p>The full computation is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{1}{6} + \frac{1}{5} + \frac{1}{10}
      \amp = \frac{1 \cdot 5}{6 \cdot 5} + \frac{1 \cdot 6}{5 \cdot 6} + \frac{1 \cdot 3}{10 \cdot 3} \\
      \amp = \frac{5}{30} + \frac{6}{30} + \frac{3}{30} \\
      \amp = \frac{5+6+3}{30} \\
      \amp = \frac{14}{30} \\
        \amp = {{\frac{7}{15}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Don<rsq/>t forget to reduce the fraction <m>\frac{14}{30}</m> by dividing <m>2</m> into both the numerator and the denominator.</p>
</solution>
